defaultQuestion 1: defaultDo you think the Government should introduce a biodiversity offsetting system in England? 
default&#xa0;
defaultYes, very much so. We have been 
defaultmaking the case for market based solutions, to environmental problems, including offsetting, since 2009 and the publication of our report “Private Solutions to Public Problems”.
defaultIn an age of austerity, 
defaultwe need to be looking at new ways to pay 
defaultfor biodivers
defaultity. 
defaultEven if the budget for the new CAP is only marginally less than the current one, it is unlikely that there will be sufficient public funds to do meet all of society’s aspirations in the long term.  One of the most straightforward ways of levering in m
defaultore funding is through ecosystems markets by which those who benefit from the provision of environmental  services contribute to the costs; particularly developers being required to provide offsets to replace 
defaultthe loss of 
defaultbiodiversity as a condition of obta
defaultining planning permission. 
defaultSimilarly, there is of course the requirement for the 
defaultprovision of compensatory habitat under the Habitats Directive. 
defaultHowever, we would emphasise that 
defaultall 
defaultthese arrangements will only find favour with landowners if they enter
default in
defaultto them 
defaultvoluntarily. 
defaultAny system based on or involving the comp
defaultulsory acquisition of land will
default be unacceptable to the vast majority of landowners. 
defaultAs such we see 
defaultoffsetting 
defaultas being primarily a commercial matter with the landowner deciding that he wishes to dedicate his land for conservation purposes so long as the price is right. 
defaultQuestion 2: defaultD
defaulto you think the Government’s objectives for the system and the characteristics the
default Government thinks a system would display are right? 
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough we do not claim to speak for the sort of developers likely to be obliged to provide offsets, we think that anything that brings certainty to the planning system by enabling developers to predi
defaultct from the outset what is expected of them will result in a faster 
defaultand almost certainly cheaper 
defaultsystem. Nevertheless, the system must not have the effect of making much needed small scale developments in the countryside unviable. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe strongly believe tha
defaultt offsetting will bring net benefits for biodiversity. 
defaultWe agree with the proposed characteristics. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 3: defaultDo you think it is appropriate to base an offsetting system on the pilot metric? If not is there an alternative metric that should be used? 
default&#xa0;
defaultW
defaulte support the aspiration that the metric needs to be both simple and able to cope with a range of habitat types.  We are not aware of any other metric which better achieves this.
default&#xa0;
