defaultQuestion 5: defaultDo you think offsetting assessment should be used when preparing a planning application for a pr
defaultoject? 
default&#xa0;
defaultYes, subject to considerations such as thresholds.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuesdefaulttion 6default:default defaultD
defaulto you agree that it should be the responsibility of planning authorities to ensure the mitigation hierarchy is observed and decide what offset is required to compensate for any 
defaultresidual loss
default?  
defaultIf not, why, and how do you think offsetting should be approached in the planning system? 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do think it should be the responsibility of the planning authority.  But we are very conscious of the need to avoid placing additional burdens on
default developers. 
defaultThe amount of information a developer is obliged to supply in support of an application is already excessive. 
defaultAs such we suggest a short statement
default, for consideration by the planning authority, 
defaultsetting out how he has complied with the hierarchy
default should be sufficient. 
defaultIf a developer is required to spend time and money in obtaining consultants reports it will defeat one of the main objectives of offsetting. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 7: defaultDo you think biodiversity offsetting should have a role in all development con
defaultsent regimes?
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultYes. We see no reason to differentiate between the various terrestrial development consent 
defaultregimes. We would support the introduction of an offsetting obligation for HS2
default and 
defaultother
default large infrastructure projects.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 8: defaultDo you think developers should be able to choose whether to use offsetting? If so what steps could Government take to encourage developers to use offsetting? 
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough instinctively we would prefer a voluntary approach we suspect, to be viable, the system will need to 
defaultbe mandatory
default, subject to thresholds, 
defaultboth in terms of the 
defaultassessment and 
defaultthe requirement 
defaultto offset
default.  Unless the system is mandatory we 
defaultdoubt we 
defaultwi
defaultll be able to ensure the level of investor confidence required to produce the number of offset sites required. Landowners will not think it worth their while looking into offsetting if there are only a few random developers looking for offsets. 
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion default9default: defaultIf
default you think developers should be required to use offsetting do you think this requirement should only apply above a threshold based on the size of the development? What level should the threshold be? 
default&#xa0;
defaultYes.  We support the use of thresholds rather than
default requirements to assess the significance of the developments impact. 
defaultFrom our experiences with the concept
default’
defaults use under the Habitats Regulations and the EIA Directive, s
defaultignificance
default is 
defaultdifficult to measure and invariably requires the use of consultants.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWe suggest that the threshold should be based on the viability of the development.  It should certainly not be so low as to discourage the small scale developments in rural villages or settlements tha
defaultt are required to deal
default with the lack
default of housing in the c
defaultountryside.
default On this basis we believe it should be at least 10 units. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no discussion in the consultation paper about what the thresholds would be for other developments, such as road building. We suggest there should be no thresholds in such cases
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 10default:default defaultDo you think there should be constraints on where offsets can be located? If so what constraints do you think should be put in place? 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe location of offsets is a difficult issue. We can see merits in consolidating the offsets resulting 
defaultfrom a number of small developments in one location to create something bigger and better, or to fill in the gaps between protected sites as per the Lawton report.  
default&#xa0;
defaultMoreover, if 
defaultthere is a
default requirement that the offset must be local to the development, the
defaultre may be a difficulty with the number of potential offset providers available. In some localities with only a small number of landowners, those landowners could charge “ransom values” to provide the requisite offsets. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNevertheless, we understand the con
defaultcerns that 
defaultsuch an approach may result in the offset being some distance from the related development and local people suffering the possible detrimental impact of the development without obtaining the benefit of the offset.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAs such whilst the offset do
defaultes not have to be next to the development it should not be too far away
default.  
defaultAs a compromise between these various factors we suggest that
default,
default at 
defaultthe very least
default,
default the
default development and the offset 
defaultshould be in the same county, although we 
defaultappreciate that this is not
default an ideal situation. If you develop on the northern border of a county then your perfect offsetting site may be a mile away across the boundary and you may be searching for a suitable site 30 miles away further south to stay with the same county
default.
default 
defaultIt may be
default that localities based on other than 
defaultadministrative 
defaultboundaries could also be used, such as water catchments.
default 
default&#xa0;
