defaultQuestion 2default4:default defaultHow long should offsets be secured for? 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are pleased the question has been asked. The presumption that offsets should be secured in perpetuity has been a parti
defaultcular cause for concern.  We think it fundamentally wrong to dictate the use of a particular piece of land for ever. We suggest that few people would think that a land use determined in 1813 still had any great relevance, and similarly that in 2213, few wi
defaultll think a use set now was still appropriate. Moreover, we suspect that many landowners will see little that is attractive about 
defaultdedicating land in perpetuity. 
defaultThey might as well sell it. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs such, we suggest that the default position should be something 
defaultless than perpetu
defaultity –
default66
default years may be a more reasonable timescale. 
default In any event a 
defaultcertain amount of flex
defaultibility in the management plan will be required so that 
defaultso that it can adapt in the l
defaultight of changing circumstances.
defaultQuestion 25default:default defaultA
defaultre there any long-term factors, besides climate change, that should be taken into account when securing offsets? 
default&#xa0;
defaultStatutory designations allow for revocations or modifications in the light of changing circumstances.  We see no reason why conservation cove
defaultnants should be any different.  Climate change, in particular  will result in many changes to the uses to which particular land can be put and will also impact on the location o
defaultf suitable habitats for certain 
defaultspecies, as such we should be encouraging the d
defaultevelopment of flexible structures. 
defaultAttention should also be given to other sources of biodiversity funding. 
default In particular, with the increasing probability that the CAP budget
default will be significantly reduced 
defaultover the coming years, the need to secure other s
defaultources of funding becomes all the greater. 
defaultQuestion 26: defaultDo you think biodiversity offsetting should be” backdated” so it can apply in relation to any planning applications under consideration at the point it is introduced?
default&#xa0;
defaultWe see no reason why it should 
defaultnot be introduced on the basis that the developer can volunteer to provide an offset rather than go through the s.106 procedure.  If it were mandatory we can envisage developers who had already begun commissioning reports in anticipation of having to negot
defaultiate a s.106 agreement being prejudiced. 
defaultQuestion 27: defaultDo you think an offsetting system should take a national approach to the question of significant harm and if so how? 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs noted
default above, an obligation to asses
defaults significance creates uncertainty and expenditure. We would very much prefer the test to be based on thresholds. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 28: defaultDo you think any additional mechanisms need to be put in place to secure offsets beyond conservation covenants? If so why and w
defaulthat are they? If this includes measures not listed above, please explain what they are. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe developer is bound by a requirement to acquire an offset by the terms of the planning permission.  If the developer does not provide it personally it will do so o
defaultn the basis of a contract with an offset provider. 
defaultIn either instance there are sufficient enforcem
defaultent mechanisms available. The pl
defaultanning authority can enforce ag
defaultainst the de
defaultveloper and the developer can take action und
defaulte
defaultr the contract with the provider. 
defaultWe 
defaultsuggest that for 
defaultconservation covenant
defaults
default 
defaultto be an effective mechanism certain additional mechanisms should be put in place.  Firstly they 
defaultshould be 
defaultable to be 
defaultregist
defaulte
defaultred
default as a
default 
defaultlocal land charge, and that from the date wh
defaulten a conservation covenant is 
defaultregis
defaulttered it will be enforceable against successors in title to the original 
defaultcovenantor.
default&#xa0;
defaultSecondly, injunctions and contractual damages should be available to the beneficiary of the covenant in the event of the covenant being breached.  However
default,
default t
defaulthe only circu
defaultmstances in which we can see 
defaultexemplary damages 
defaultbeing legitimate is where the perpetrator has committed the act with a view to making a financial gain.  Exempl
defaultary damages could be ordered which would effectively
default confiscate it. 
defaultWe do not believe these contractual remedies should be available to any third party, including the state.  It is a matter of a private agreement between the parties. 
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 29: defaultDo you think there should be constraints on what habitat can be provided as
